body:
@N-Coder I think what you're proposing can be broken down into two separate (but related) issues:
1. We already have a long-polled events interface, where lots async data appears, without it having to be polled for. Putting stuff that's currently being polled for (model updates, errors, etc) onto the events interface would significantly reduce the amount of polling. This is (as I understand it) what @calmh's referenced commit does.
2. The events interface doesn't have to be long-polled: using websockets would be another option here, and one that might be worth considering. However do bear in mind that the majority of Syncthing's REST API clients _aren't_ web browsers. We've got cli interfaces, custom GIUs, tray icons, you name it, interacting with Syncthing in this way. A long-polled interface is easy to write a client for: a websockets interface is tricky if you don't have a library available.
